Answer:
&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first version is correct, as without braces, only &lt;strong&gt;one&lt;/strong&gt; statement after the &lt;code&gt;if&lt;/code&gt; statement applies to the conditions of the &lt;code&gt;if&lt;/code&gt; statement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;if ($something) $this-&amp;gt;some_function($str);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is equivalent to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;if ($something) {
    $this-&amp;gt;some_function($str);
}
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I do agree that &lt;a href="http://php.net/manual/en/control-structures.if.php" rel="nofollow"&gt;the manual&lt;/a&gt; is a bit vague about this, but its example is about a single statement, and mentions that in order to incorporate additional lines to the same conditional, you would need a "statement group", denoted by curly braces:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Often you'd want to have more than one statement to be executed
  conditionally. Instead, you can group several statements into a
  statement group.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

